column7: Principal Data Scientist I – Let’s get started!
The Secret To A Successful YouTube Business
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you’ve had a great week so far.

Quick couple of things before we start:

* In case you missed our announcement video yesterday, we’ve just
launched our second app Momentum: Energising Habits (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hngvez9u6h9k8e444cnh30xrv/48hvh7umrpv9v9fq/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL2NyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcy95dGJpel8xMA==
) 🎉 It’s all focussed on helping you stay consistent with your
habits (like creating content 👀) and leverages the power of
accountability, through our Squads feature, to help really
supercharge your personal productivity. You can download it here
(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hngvez9u6h9k8e444cnh30xrv/48hvh7umrpv9v9fq/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL2NyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcy95dGJpel8xMA==
) - check it out and let me know your thoughts, always keen for
feedback 🙏
* Secondly, we’ve finalised a date for the next quarterly reset
workshop. It’s going to be happening next Saturday (20th
September), and you can register by just clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hngvez9u6h9k8e444cnh30xrv/x0hwppx4i3uewpozodig/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8=
).

Anyway, on with today’s email where I wanted to share some more
content from one of our recent guest workshops.

Since a lot of you have been enjoying these emails about building
a successful YouTube business, I thought I’d share a piece of
content about one of the most overlooked steps when it comes to
creating something to sell: knowing your audience.

Whether you’re trying to turn the audience you’ve already built
into a business or starting a YouTube channel with the sole
purpose of growing your business, understanding your audience is
incredibly important.

Why? Because when you really know your audience - who they are,
where they live, what problems they have, what their goals are,
stuff like that - you can create offers that people actually want
instead of wasting time, energy, and money building something
nobody cares about.

This is something Tintin, my former YouTube producer as many of
you know, has gotten really good at. He’s built a 6-figure
business helping educational creators monetise their channels
using his 4-step roadmap: generating leads, creating offers,
building products, and scaling.

And the clip below focuses specifically on the middle part - how
to research your audience properly and use those insights to
create the right product that people will actually buy.

-->👉 Watch the video (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hngvez9u6h9k8e444cnh30xrv/reh8h9um03474ec6/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2J1aWxkLXRoZS1yaWdodC1vZmZlci1mb3IteW91ci1hdWRpZW5jZS8=
)
👉 Watch the video (
https://aliabdaal.com/build-the-right-offer-for-your-audience/
)This kind of strategic thinking about your audience and offers
is exactly what we dive into within the final module of PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hngvez9u6h9k8e444cnh30xrv/08hwhgu2d9vxv7sp/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXl0Yml6XzEwJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
), where we cover how to make money both on and off YouTube. And
if you’re keen to read more about Tintin’s 100k Roadmap
specifically, you can check that out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hngvez9u6h9k8e444cnh30xrv/8ghqh3uol2z3zgul/aHR0cHM6Ly8xMDBrcm9hZG1hcC5jby8=
).

Oh and if you want to watch the full workshop where Tintin and
Angus go through the complete roadmap and go into more detail on
products and offers too, it’s all included when you sign up to
PTYA - click here to join (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hngvez9u6h9k8e444cnh30xrv/08hwhgu2d9vxv7sp/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXl0Yml6XzEwJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
).

Anyway, I hope today’s content was useful - have a great week 🙌

Talk soon,

Ali xx

column8: The "D" In Data Stands For Discipline
column10:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/the-d-in-data-stands-for-discipline

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here 👋
Before diving in to that, I wanted to let y’all know that I’ll be running several events in person in the UK, Seattle and Denver. The first will be in the UK, so if you’d like to join me after Big Data London, you can sign up here [ https://substack.com/redirect/df09f9ac-3b10-40c0-9d8f-6af5140d2c0a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]! 
Also, special thanks to Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/f7a815cc-691b-4625-ad84-94809f7b3479?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] for partnering on this event!
Food and drinks will be provided as well as a live band!
Now let’s jump into the article!
A seasoned data leader once told me something that stuck: the d in data stands for discipline.
Now to be clear, pretty much every field requires discipline.
But we often focus on the exciting parts of data work in articles. 
Not the tedious, repetitive, mundane, just doing the right thing type work.
It is those unglamorous but critical habits that help you deliver good work:
Resisting the urge to over-engineer a simple problem
Enforcing standards even when it feels tedious
Saying “no” to the ad-hoc requests that would derail your team from finishing meaningful work
Committing to an idea even if it doesn’t provide immediate results
None of these are flashy. They don’t exactly make for a good case study or talk at a conference. But looking back into my article from a couple weeks ago. But they are more habits that I’ve seen separate good and great data teams.
There are plenty of benefits from doing all the small things well.
Below are three ways discipline shows up in a high-performing data teams.
Practicing Restraint In Data Infrastructure Choices
Here I often think back to my early cooking days. As a young cook, I’d pile every technique I knew onto a single plate. I wasn’t thinking about the diner’s experience. I really was just showing off.
Over time I learned that every component must earn its place.
In the same way, data infrastructure is a tempting place to use tool after tool and build a massively complex system to report churn.
It’s tempting to keep adding tools, Iceberg, Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/89bd07b8-4056-49e3-94b5-e7ccb655b04d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/aa7f8dee-43ae-4b07-9522-1c80cfdbddd5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Airflow [ https://substack.com/redirect/17fbfa39-f4f9-4c19-a0ca-b3ad769714c7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Sigma, Unity Catalog, until the stack looks impressive on paper. Yet, I’ve seen teams [ https://substack.com/redirect/b08604c6-a805-4eaf-98fe-cde99c3425e2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] spend millions building these sprawling setups only to hear the same complaint from business leaders:
“I can’t find the numbers I need”
So technically, you might have built an amazing data infrastructure stack but functionally for the business no one uses it. 
So why did you build it?
Saying No to the Endless Ad-Hoc Ask - And Actually Finishing Work
Data teams can quickly become the company’s catch-all IT fill-in department.
One day it’s a finance team automation, the next it’s a one-off dashboard or an urgent “just pull this number” request. Each ask might seem harmless, but together they create a flood that pulls the team away from meaningful, long-term work.
Data teams need to have the discipline to say “No”.
Now I say “No” but I mean, you need to be able to communicate what your team can and can’t get done and what trade offs are.
It’s also about ensuring your team isn’t constantly getting ripped from one project to another.
After all:
“you only get value from projects when they finish: to make progress, above all else, you must ensure that some of your projects finish.”
― Will Larson [ https://substack.com/redirect/85853325-214f-4970-93a1-a151b0b34e3a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], An Elegant Puzzle: Systems of Engineering Management
If you let your data team get steam-rolled and just say yes to every ad-hoc request, at first other leaders might enjoy how much attention they are getting, then they will keep asking for more and more and your data team will get burnt out, projects won’t get fully delivered and things will just continue to unravel.
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Following Standards Relentlessly
Standards cover everything from how tables are named to how version control is handled, how SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/febfc407-2c83-42b1-8c64-02b4e443aa34?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] is formatted, and how data models are structured [ https://substack.com/redirect/e81b4d38-b8be-4836-95e7-dea84a14c186?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. 
I don’t view these are not just cosmetic choices. Consistency ensures that a query written today will still be understandable (and trustworthy) six months from now.
Now in the past this meant I’d have to go over my SQL scripts and ensure that I tabbed everything as expected. 
Luckily now you can automate this part of “discipline”. You can do so by making those standards part of the process. Use linting tools, CI/CD checks, and code reviews so that every pull request is validated before it ever hits production. When we did this at Facebook nits went down 98%(Or at least that’s what it felt like).
Documentation is part of the standard. A living style guide and onboarding [ https://substack.com/redirect/befe83ee-0681-410b-9cc2-b0ba73bd31c7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] guide help new team members ramp up quickly, reducing the “legacy knowledge” that can paralyze a team when someone leaves.
This also makes it easier for external team members to quickly understand what your naming conventions and workflows look like.
It also makes future migrations, looking through code for specific patterns and a whole host of other larger projects considerably easier. 
But Wait There Is More!
Now there are plenty of other ways data teams remained disciplined when it comes to delivering the right end products to the business. If you’d like to read some of my past articles on some of the topics you can see them below.
Keeping focused on the business [ https://substack.com/redirect/8266cd01-4ea1-4014-8ff1-92d51cf43143?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Not letting hype derail what actually matters [ https://substack.com/redirect/68c2f671-a6bb-4c43-ad99-410bcc6de94b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Building production ready data pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/4c8f6f73-990e-4217-a12e-91c94d9aaf5f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Final Thoughts
So many projects and data stacks I’ve seen fall apart because of small compromises that built up over time. 
There was no clear owner for a task or larger process.
The data engineering team used a tool to patch a problem rather than inquiring why they were having the issue.
No one set standards which allowed for fast development at first until the first migration.
Each small compromise seems harmless in the moment, but together they create technical debt, brittle pipelines, and future pains.
There is always a balance of course, you don’t want to put so much process in the way that nothing moves.
But you also want to avoid building a big ball of mud that no one wants to touch.
As always, thanks for reading.
Upcoming Data Events
Airflow Summit 2025(I’ll be there!) [ https://substack.com/redirect/c0ec9510-ce46-427d-834d-d86e86189ac0?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
London Is Calling - Data And Drinks With Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/df09f9ac-3b10-40c0-9d8f-6af5140d2c0a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Coffee With The Seattle Data Guy - London [ https://substack.com/redirect/2a6125a3-cb6f-469d-a39a-6f00c2b690b1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Big Data London(I’ll be there!) [ https://substack.com/redirect/b184ddd2-96d8-4e6e-a5ad-d11ad1381ec3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Is TV's Golden Age (Officially) Over? A Statistical Analysis
By Daniel Parris  
A lot can change in forty-five months. Think back to November of 2021: the world had yet to see a Tesla Cybertruck, HBO Max was an ascendant streaming service, Will Smith had slapped zero people on live television, Sam Bankman-Fried was a benevolent billionaire and model citizen, and Netflix's stock was soaring, buoyed by the pandemic.
And then the unthinkable happened: Netflix reported a quarterly loss of 200,000 subscribers. This earnings miss—coupled with broader economic uncertainty—triggered widespread panic across the entertainment industry. Streaming platforms slashed their content budgets, media conglomerates like Disney and Warner Bros. laid off thousands, and Netflix's stock fell by 51%. This industry-wide contraction culminated in a six-month writers’ strike, as unions demanded higher pay, standardized compensation, and greater residuals. Amid full work stoppages and a volatile economy, industry pundits began speculating whether streaming could recapture its pre-2022 momentum.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/bbf6bac0-93f6-4a5c-85bc-f62d844e1915?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
The Pedantic Layer
By Joe Reis  
In the data world, we love to argue about definitions. What is unstructured data? Is JSON structured or semi-structured? Are PDFs unstructured, or do they contain “implicit structure”? Do LLM embeddings of text count as structured data? And WTF is a semantic layer [ https://substack.com/redirect/ea43e5fd-13df-4056-b540-f706a5bc3f9b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]? Entire threads, articles, and even conference talks spin out of these debates.
This obsession forms what I call the Pedantic Layer…
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/7fe82ea9-a0c1-443c-857c-09099e76d25f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

column7: Got access to OpenAI's Operator & recorded while trying it our for the 1st time
column9:
View this post on the web at https://marily.substack.com/p/got-access-to-openais-operator-and

Got access to OpenAI's Operator! I recorded while trying it for the 1st time - just made a dinner reservation. Pretty amazing.
Thoughts:
✨ I really enjoyed not having to do the groundwork like searching for the restaurant, inputting the details
✨ This basically has a model that combines multimodal capabilities with mouse and keyboard control to act on your behalf
✨ There’s a built-in browser so you can see what Operator is doing in real time. I also liked that I could take control or hand it back whenever I wanted.
✨ It was slower than I expected, but honestly, that didn’t bother me much—it was just surprising.
✨ I wish it were more proactive. Memory could help here so it can learn from how I interact over time.
✨ What’s really missing is voice interaction. Once I can use this seamlessly via voice, it will truly feel like a game changer.
Overall, pretty amazing and the beginning of a new way of achieving things.
If you want free 12-months of perplexity pro, upgrade to a paid subscriber! Codes go out at 5pm today.

column7: What Being a Doctor Taught Me About Prioritisation
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you had a great weekend 🙌

Over the past few weeks, I’ve been finding myself being pulled in
even more directions than usual - finalising everything for our
founding cohort of the Lifestyle Business Academy, tinkering away
on app stuff behind the scenes, filming YouTube videos, and just
the usual operational fluff that comes with running a business.

Having to juggle quite a fair bit, it’s definitely reminded me of
one of the biggest productivity lessons I’ve had to relearn
multiple times over the years: the skill of knowing when (and
how) to say no.

Now this might not be the most revolutionary insight ever, but
saying no is really all about prioritisation, and you’d be
surprised to hear just how many people (including me) still
struggle with this.

A lot of us find ourselves in a situation where we tick a bunch
of things off on our to-do list, but we get to the end of the day
thinking “huh, I feel like I did a lot of stuff… but I don’t feel
like I made a lot of progress.”

We’ve basically had loads of movement, but not much meaningful
motion on the things that actually matter.

Back when I worked as a doctor, I realised pretty quickly that if
you spend your entire shift doing all the low priority tasks like
chasing bloods, filling in forms, or responding to every bleep,
you’re going to run into trouble pretty quickly. Because that’s
not actually the job of a doctor.

The job of a doctor isn’t to do everything on the to-do list. The
job is to do the most important things on the to-do list.

So if a patient’s having a heart attack, you literally have to
drop everything and sprint across the hospital to deal with that.
The less urgent stuff has to wait (or just not get done at all
that day) because you were busy keeping someone alive.

Now I’d extend that principle to all of us as competent
professionals who are trying to make the most of our time and
achieve our goals: our real objective isn’t to try and do
everything, because that would be a recipe for failure and
burnout. Our real objective is to make sure we’re prioritising
the most important things.

And so in every moment, we need to be asking ourselves: “Is this
thing I’m about to do really the most important thing I could be
doing right now?”

This requires being comfortable with letting some things go and
embracing mediocrity - or at least “good enough” - in a lot of
areas of our lives if we want to make real, meaningful progress
in others.

For example, there may well be seasons of your life where you’re
taking on a new work project so you don’t reply to every WhatsApp
message in the group chat or every email that comes your way.
There may also be seasons where work takes a bit of a backseat
because you want to be present with your family (I’m definitely
realising this a lot at the moment as a new dad).

But that’s not failure - that’s just life and what intentional
prioritisation looks like in practice.

Now if you want to properly figure out what’s actually important,
you need to have clarity on your goals, and you’ll find a bunch
of tools and strategies to help you do this within LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh24lx37trh4ldgonns7h6x45l/kkhmh2un6gnwm2ak/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXByaW9yaXRpc2F0aW9uXzI3JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
).

Vision is one of the two key pillars of the course, where we help
you figure out what you actually want to do with your life and
which direction you want to head in, so if you’ve been feeling
like you’re constantly busy but not making meaningful progress,
it might be worth checking it out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh24lx37trh4ldgonns7h6x45l/kkhmh2un6gnwm2ak/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXByaW9yaXRpc2F0aW9uXzI3JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
).

Anyway, I hope today’s email was useful, and feel free to share
any thoughts on how you manage your priorities in your own life -
hit reply and let me know!

Have a great week!

Ali xx
